      Aluminum arbitrage
   =20
 =20
There are two kinds of aluminum:=09Physical aluminum, which some industrial=
 producer or trader of aluminum delivers to some actual user of aluminum, w=
ho then uses it to make beer cans or whatever; and=09Abstract aluminum, whi=
ch lives in warehouses associated with the London Metal Exchange, and which=
 is used to underpin LME=C2=A0futures=C2=A0contracts. If you buy an aluminu=
m futures contract on the LME, and it expires and you =E2=80=9Ctake deliver=
y=E2=80=9D of the aluminum, what you actually get is a receipt =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0called a =E2=80=9Cwarrant=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0entitling you to some =
of the aluminum in an LME warehouse. And then you can sell that warrant, or=
 use it to sell futures; you never need to take the metail out of the wareh=
ouse. We talked last year about JPMorgan Chase & Co.=E2=80=99s discovery th=
at some of the nickel it owned, in LME warehouses, was actually bags of roc=
ks that had apparently been there for years. Understandable! JPMorgan was n=
ot making batteries with the nickel; it was making futures contracts. The p=
hysical properties of the nickel (or, rocks) were not that relevant. =E2=80=
=9CLike Yap money stones,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe warehouse nic=
kel is still useful for financial trading even if it is not actually there,=
 or not actually nickel.=E2=80=9DThe economics of this system are quite biz=
arre. Physical aluminum=C2=A0costs more=C2=A0than abstract aluminum, becaus=
e you can use it to make beer cans. Abstract aluminum costs less, because y=
ou can=E2=80=99t. Abstract aluminum=C2=A0can, however, be transformed into =
actual aluminum. (Unless it is rocks.) It=E2=80=99s the same physical subst=
ance; it=E2=80=99s just in different warehouses.=C2=A0You can go to an LME =
warehouse with your warrant and demand that they give you your aluminum, an=
d they will.=C2=A0This would seem to create an arbitrage: Buy aluminum on t=
he LME for cheap, get the warrant, hand in the warrant, get the aluminum, a=
nd sell it in the physical market for more money.Why doesn=E2=80=99t this w=
ork? The stylized answer is something like: Because the door to the LME war=
ehouse is really small, and the people working there take long lunch breaks=
, so if you go to the warehouse with a warrant for 100 tons of aluminum it =
will take them ages to give it to you. Just the delay itself is bad for the=
 arbitrage =E2=80=94=C2=A0you buy low in the notional market and then have =
to wait ages for delivery to sell high in the physical market, subject to m=
arket risk=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but also you pay=C2=A0rent, to the warehouse=
, while you are waiting for your aluminum. So if the physical market price =
is much higher than the abstract market price, everyone will notice the arb=
itrage and try to take aluminum out of the warehouses, which will make the =
delay much longer, so everyone will have to pay a lot of rent while they wa=
it, so even if they do end up selling the physical aluminum for a higher pr=
ice than they paid on the LME, they might end up with a loss.The point here=
 is that there is a flavor of aluminum trading that is not =E2=80=9Canticip=
ate whether the price of aluminum will go up or down, and bet on that,=E2=
=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Canticipate whether there will be a long line to =
get aluminum out of the warehouse, and bet on=C2=A0that.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=
=99re not trading =E2=80=9Cthe price of aluminum=E2=80=9D but rather, like,=
 =E2=80=9Cthe expected rent cost of the delay in taking aluminum out of the=
 warehouse.=E2=80=9D You are trading the warehouse delay, not the commodity=
.And this trade is of course two-sided. If the line to take aluminum out of=
 the warehouse is long, you can put aluminum=C2=A0in=C2=A0the warehouse and=
=C2=A0capture=C2=A0some of that rent. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Jack Farchy,=
 Mark Burton=C2=A0and Archie Hunter have a story about Trafigura Group that=
 I=E2=80=99m sure is very normal and straightforward to commodity traders b=
ut still strikes me as hilarious. =E2=80=9CTrafigura has been accumulating =
a stockpile of aluminum in Port Klang [in Malaysia]=C2=A0over the past year=
,=E2=80=9D physical aluminum outside of the LME system, and people wondered=
 what it would do with all that aluminum:Often, traders accumulating large =
stashes see opportunities to profit from increases in the physical premium =
that buyers pay over and above the LME price. If demand outstrips supply, t=
he location-specific premiums tend to rise as real-world consumers of alumi=
num draw down metal that=E2=80=99s held in stockpiles.Instead, in the past =
two weeks, about 650,000 tons of aluminum sitting in Port Klang was suddenl=
y transferred on to LME warrant. Trafigura was the key player behind the de=
liveries, which led to an increase in live warrants of more than 500,000 to=
ns on May 10 =E2=80=94 the largest single-day delivery onto the LME in at l=
east 27 years.A few days after the deliveries began, Trafigura laid out its=
 bearish outlook at a conference in London. Analyst Henry Van predicted tha=
t aluminum prices would fall, saying it was seeing =E2=80=9Ca very grim dem=
and picture right now,=E2=80=9D and noting recent smelter restarts.Trafigur=
a had aluminum and was bearish,=C2=A0so it wanted to sell it. But instead o=
f selling physical aluminum, Trafigura popped its aluminum into the LME sys=
tem =E2=80=94=C2=A0where it was worth less=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and sold it =
there, missing out on the physical premium but profiting from (1) how many =
other traders were bullish on aluminum, (2) how many of them wanted physica=
l aluminum=C2=A0and (3) how small the door is:Other traders are taking the =
opposite view. Of the metal delivered on to LME warrant in the past two wee=
ks, about 400,000 tons =E2=80=94 worth about $1 billion at current prices =
=E2=80=94 was quickly requested for delivery out again. =E2=80=A6The decisi=
on to offload the mountain of stock on to the LME has puzzled many of Trafi=
gura=E2=80=99s competitors in the aluminum market, and the scramble to get =
hold of it has underscored its value to rival traders. Facing soft trading =
conditions in the physical market, Trafigura may have taken the view that t=
he quickest and most lucrative way to turn a profit on the metal would be t=
o sell it on the LME and collect a share of the rent from future owners.Tra=
ders delivering large volumes to the LME generally enter =E2=80=9Crent shar=
e=E2=80=9D deals with the warehouse company they=E2=80=99re delivering to, =
meaning they earn a share of the revenues for as long as the metal stays in=
 the warehouse. At a rent of 56 cents a day, the total rent on 650,000 tons=
 of aluminum could be worth as much as $133 million a year =E2=80=94 more t=
han $200 a ton =E2=80=94 as long as it stays where it is.If it=E2=80=99s al=
l requested for delivery, the total earnings would be a fraction of that am=
ount. Still, it is guaranteed to earn a certain amount of money =E2=80=94 a=
bout $40 a ton in rent =E2=80=94 because the metal is only delivered out at=
 a rate of a few thousand tons a day.The big orders for withdrawal of alumi=
num have already led to a long queue to take delivery from warehouses in Po=
rt Klang operated by Istim Metals. The LME has rules to limit rents as soon=
 as warehouse queues exceed a certain threshold, which it introduced after =
spiralling backlogs for aluminum drew consumer ire and regulatory scrutiny =
a decade ago.The obvious question is something like =E2=80=9Cif Trafigura h=
ad a lot of aluminum outside of the LME warehouses that it wanted to sell, =
and a lot of people wanted to buy a lot of aluminum outside of the LME ware=
houses, why didn=E2=80=99t they just trade with each other and skip the lin=
e?=E2=80=9D But the answer is apparently that Trafigura analyzed the line a=
nd decided it would be more profitable.
