My simple model of private credit=C2=A0is:=09In the olden days, insurance c=
ompanies were in the business of lending money to companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
by buying bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0and holding the bonds to maturity.=09This wa=
s a sensible model for them, since they had locked-up customer money and lo=
ng-term predictable=C2=A0liability schedules, so they could easily hold the=
 bonds to maturity.=09Then Bill Gross invented the idea of trading bonds, w=
hich allowed insurance companies to make some excess returns (by selling ov=
erpriced bonds and buying underpriced ones).
  [2]
=09This was such a good idea that (1) the bond market became reasonably act=
ively traded and efficient, (2) the idea spread far beyond insurance compan=
ies (to the point that Bill Gross himself managed huge bond portfolios for =
other institutions and individuals) and (3) the edge you could get from it =
was largely competed away.=09Some insurance companies looked around and sai=
d =E2=80=9Cwait, we are insurance companies. We can buy and hold bonds unti=
l maturity. If we lend money to companies directly, rather than through the=
 big liquid modern bond market, maybe we can charge a higher rate and make =
more money.=E2=80=9D=09This was a sensible model for them, since they had l=
ocked-up customer money and long-term predictable liability schedules, so t=
hey could easily hold the loans to maturity.In a sense, this is a story of =
things coming full circle: 1950s insurance companies loaned money to compan=
ies and held to maturity without trading the bonds, and in 2024 that is als=
o all the rage. But there is an important=C2=A0cultural=C2=A0difference. In=
 the 1950s, if you did this sort of thing, you worked in the bond departmen=
t of an insurance company, and that was a boring and relatively low-status =
job that involved literally clipping paper coupons off bonds and mailing th=
em to the company to get your interest payment.In the 2020s, if you do this=
 sort of thing, you work for the=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cprivate credit department=E2=
=80=9D of=C2=A0an =E2=80=9Calternative asset manager,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and it=
=E2=80=99s a hot high-status job of pitching to finance=C2=A0leveraged buyo=
uts. The insurance companies are still providing (a chunk=C2=A0of) the mone=
y: They are often limited partners in the private credit funds run by=C2=A0=
the alternative asset managers, and in some cases they are owned by the alt=
ernative asset managers.
  [3]
=C2=A0But the people=C2=A0managing=C2=A0the money =E2=80=94=C2=A0finding an=
d negotiating=C2=A0and monitoring the private loans =E2=80=94=C2=A0are more=
 specialized and get paid more.Today=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Silas Br=
own, Paula Seligson, and Esteban Duarte have a story about the bond departm=
ent of Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. Wait, no, sorry, that=E2=80=
=99s wrong: They have a story about the private credit (=E2=80=9CGlobal Pri=
vate Finance=E2=80=9D) team at Barings LLC, an investment management firm t=
hat happens to be owned by MassMutual. The Barings private credit team had =
a mass defection (and accompanying lawsuits) in March, apparently because =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0they didn=E2=80=99t want to work at an insurance company?In =
a March move that stunned the relatively genteel world of private credit, 2=
2 Barings employees quit en masse and jumped ship for an obscure startup ca=
lled Corinthia Global Management Ltd., run by Australian real-estate entrep=
reneur Paul Weightman =E2=80=94 a combative figure known to some as =E2=80=
=9CWeighty.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6According to Weightman and others with knowle=
dge of the matter, the GPF defectors have been seduced in part by the promi=
se of equity in his firm, something that wasn=E2=80=99t on the menu at Bari=
ngs. While some staffers were making more than $1 million a year, that=E2=
=80=99s a fraction of the tens of millions of dollars made by senior peers =
who=E2=80=99ve cashed in stakes at smaller boutique rivals such as Arcmont =
Asset Management.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6Tensions at GPF had been building for a whi=
le, people familiar with the matter say. Many in the team didn=E2=80=99t fe=
el adequately backed by Barings and its owner, US insurer MassMutual, with =
some complaining of not getting full support for operational matters and re=
cruitment. While about 80% of MassMutual=E2=80=99s investments in middle-ma=
rket direct lending were done via Barings, it was also investing in outside=
 private credit funds =E2=80=94 another sore point.Documents seen by Bloomb=
erg show management fees and =E2=80=9Ccarry,=E2=80=9D the share of profit f=
und managers got to keep, were meaningfully lower than at rivals Ares Manag=
ement Corp. and Tikehau Capital. Some LPs say the leavers grew frustrated a=
bout revenue-sharing arrangements with Barings=E2=80=99 head honchos.Right =
you want to be the outside alternative asset manager managing money on beha=
lf of insurance companies, not the division of the insurance company whose =
own parent company is cheating on you with outside managers.
