   =20
 =20
If you traded a stock in the US last week, the trade was scheduled to settl=
e on the second business=C2=A0after the trade date. If you bought stock las=
t Monday, you got the stock on Wednesday. If you trade a stock in the US th=
is week, the trade is scheduled to settle on the first business day after t=
he trade date. If you buy stock today, you=E2=80=99ll get it tomorrow. The =
rules have changed =E2=80=94=C2=A0from T+2=C2=A0to T+1 settlement =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0in part because the 2020 meme-stock mania drew attention to the credi=
t risk involved in waiting two days to settle a stock trade, and in part, I=
 think, because everyone is faintly embarrassed that, in our modern age of =
computing and telecommunications technology, it still takes two days to exc=
hange the electronic database entry representing a share of stock for the e=
lectronic database entry representing=C2=A0some dollars. Nobody has to send=
 any couriers anywhere to settle a stock trade.=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Gr=
eg Ritchie points out that actually the US=C2=A0used=C2=A0to have T+1 settl=
ement, back in the courier days, but eventually the couriers couldn=E2=80=
=99t keep up:The T+1 era of the 1920s =E2=80=94 a decade dubbed =E2=80=9Cth=
e roaring =E2=80=9920s=E2=80=9D in part because of the amazing stock market=
 performance =E2=80=94 ended because the manual nature of transactions mean=
t it was impossible to keep up with surging trading activity. The settlemen=
t time was eventually pushed out as far as five days.That=E2=80=99s from an=
 article about how people are nervous about the transition from T+2 to T+1,=
 which will put stress=C2=A0on various bits of infrastructure. In particula=
r the foreign exchange market, which normally settles T+2, meaning that if =
you are a European investor buying US stocks, you will need to find a faste=
r-than-normal way to convert your euros into dollars to settle the stock tr=
ade. Also tomorrow =E2=80=94=C2=A0the T+1 settlement day for today=E2=80=99=
s trades, and also the T+2 settlement day for Friday=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0will be weird:Two big, immediate tests also loom for the T+1 system: Fir=
st, Wednesday=E2=80=99s so-called double settlement day, where T+2 trades f=
rom Friday come due at the same time as Tuesday=E2=80=99s T+1 transactions.=
 Then MSCI Inc.=E2=80=99s index rebalancing at the end of the week, when fu=
nds around the world tracking its gauges will be reshuffling holdings at th=
e same time.I feel like there are three ways for this all to go:=09Smoothly=
;=09Not=C2=A0smoothly, in the sense that there are widespread glitches and =
failures to settle trades that cause some economically meaningful consequen=
ces that you will read about on the Bloomberg home page and that will ultim=
ately result in a Securities and Exchange Commission report, congressional =
hearings, some financial institutions suffering huge losses and others maki=
ng huge killings; or=09Both smoothly and not smoothly, in the sense that yo=
u and I won=E2=80=99t hear of any problems, and in two weeks I will write =
=E2=80=9Cthat T+1 transition went pretty smoothly=E2=80=9D and I will get a=
 lot of emails from stock settlement professionals saying =E2=80=9Cno it wa=
s a disaster, fail rates were up, we couldn=E2=80=99t get stock borrow, the=
 system almost broke.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Right now the settlement professionals =
are the ones getting quoted about how worried they are, but in a week that =
will probably stop.
