quity firms such as KKR, Blackstone and Brookfield have since bought insure=
rs or struck deals to manage their assets.=E2=80=9D Insurers, with their lo=
ng-term money, are good customers for alternative asset managers; acquiring=
 (or being acquired by) an insurer gives you first dibs on that money; but =
that money, being insurance money, is probably looking for credit investmen=
ts (rather than private equity), so it pushes you into credit businesses.


  [4] Of course there are other ways to think about it. Probably GameStop w=
ouldn=E2=80=99t have done the offering at all at pre-Roaring Kitty prices, =
which you can tell because it *didn=E2=80=99t* do a stock offering until Gi=
ll tweeted. Also that $13.76 average price is a pretty arbitrary time perio=
d, and in the couple of weeks right before Gill=E2=80=99s tweet GameStop wa=
s trading lower.


  [5] Arguably the answer is higher than $300 million, because if you were =
*planning* this you=E2=80=99d have had the at-the-market offering ready to =
go as soon as the tweets hit, and you=E2=80=99d have gotten a much better p=
rice than $20.74. The stock was at $48.75 on May 14, while they were drafti=
ng the paperwork!


