nds of aluminum</a>:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left=
: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Physical alum=
inum, which some industrial producer or trader of aluminum delivers to some=
 actual user of aluminum, who then uses it to make beer cans or whatever; a=
nd</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Abstract aluminum, which lives =
in warehouses associated with the London Metal Exchange, and which is used =
to underpin LME=C2=A0<em>futures=C2=A0</em>contracts. If you buy an aluminu=
m futures contract on the LME, and it expires and you =E2=80=9Ctake deliver=
y=E2=80=9D of the aluminum, what you actually get is a receipt =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0called a =E2=80=9Cwarrant=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0entitling you to some =
of the aluminum in an LME warehouse. And then you can sell that warrant, or=
 use it to sell futures; you never need to take the metail out of the wareh=
ouse. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35524656.=
258330/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMt=
MjEvanBtb3JnYW4taGFkLXNvbWUtZmFrZS1uaWNrZWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyODI0X01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNT=
I4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc67b5602" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">talked last year</a> about JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co.=E2=80=99s discovery =
that some of the nickel it owned, in LME warehouses, was actually bags of r=
ocks that had apparently been there for years. Understandable! JPMorgan was=
 not making batteries with the nickel; it was making futures contracts. The=
 physical properties of the nickel (or, rocks) were not that relevant. =E2=
=80=9CLike Yap money stones,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe warehouse =
nickel is still useful for financial trading even if it is not actually the=
re, or not actually nickel.=E2=80=9D</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
The economics of this system are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/35524656.258330/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDgvdGhlLWNvZmZlZS1mdXR1cmVzLWdvdC1zdGFsZT9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQwNTI4MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MjgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBba6cb1f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">quite bizarre</a>. Physical aluminum=C2=A0<em>cos=
ts more=C2=A0</em>than abstract aluminum, because you can use it to make be=
er cans. Abstract aluminum costs less, because you can=E2=80=99t. Abstract =
aluminum=C2=A0<em>can</em>, however, be transformed into actual aluminum. (=
Unless it is rocks.) It=E2=80=99s the same physical substance; it=E2=80=99s=
 just in different warehouses.=C2=A0You can go to an LME warehouse with you=
r warrant and demand that they give you your aluminum, and they will.=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This would seem to create an arbitrage: Bu=
y aluminum on the LME for cheap, get the warrant, hand in the warrant, get =
the aluminum, and sell it in the physical market for more money.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why doesn=E2=80=99t this work? The stylized answer is=
 something like: Because the door to the LME warehouse is really small, and=
 the people working there take long lunch breaks, so if you go to the wareh=
ouse with a warrant for 100 tons of aluminum it will take them ages to give=
 it to you. Just the delay itself is bad for the arbitrage =E2=80=94=C2=A0y=
ou buy low in the notional market and then have to wait ages for delivery t=
o sell high in the physical market, subject to market risk=C2=A0=E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but also you pay=C2=A0<em>rent</em>, to the warehouse, while you are =
waiting for your aluminum. So if the physical market price is much higher t=
han the abstract market price, everyone will notice the arbitrage and try t=
o take aluminum out of the warehouses, which will make the delay much longe=
r, so everyone will have to pay a lot of rent while they wait, so even if t=
hey do end up selling the physical aluminum for a higher price than they pa=
id on the LME, they might end up with a loss.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The point here is that there is a flavor of aluminum trading that is not=
 =E2=80=9Canticipate whether the price of aluminum will go up or down, and =
bet on that,=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Canticipate whether there will be =
a long line to get aluminum out of the warehouse, and bet on=C2=A0<em>that<=
/em>.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99re not trading =E2=80=9Cthe price of aluminum=E2=
=80=9D but rather, like, =E2=80=9Cthe expected rent cost of the delay in ta=
king aluminum out of the warehouse.=E2=80=9D You are trading the warehouse =
delay, not the commodity.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And this trade is=
 of course two-sided. If the line to take aluminum out of the warehouse is =
long, you can put aluminum=C2=A0<em>in=C2=A0</em>the warehouse and=C2=A0<em=
>capture=C2=A0</em>some of that rent. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Jack Farchy,=
 Mark Burton=C2=A0and Archie Hunter <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/35524656.258330/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDUtMjUvdHJhZmlndXJhLWZhY2VzLW9mZi13aXRoLWFsdW1pbnVtLWJ1=
bGxzLW92ZXItaHVnZS1tZXRhbC1zdGFzaD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTI4MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1=
fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MjgmdXRtX2=
NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB32890657" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">have a=
 story about Trafigura Group</a> that I=E2=80=99m sure is very normal and s=
traightforward to commodity traders but still strikes me as hilarious. =E2=
=80=9CTrafigura has been accumulating a stockpile of aluminum in Port Klang=
 [in Malaysia]=C2=A0over the past year,=E2=80=9D physical aluminum outside =
of the LME system, and people wondered what it would do with all that alumi=
num:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Often, traders accumulatin=
g large stashes see opportunities to profit from increases in the physical =
premium that buyers pay over and above the LME price. If demand outstrips s=
upply, the location-specific premiums tend to rise as real-world consumers =
of aluminum draw down metal that=E2=80=99s held in stockpiles.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, in the past two weeks, about 650,000 tons of =
aluminum sitting in Port Klang was suddenly transferred on to LME warrant. =
Trafigura was the key player behind the deliveries, which led to an increas=
e in live warrants of more than 500,000 tons on May 10 =E2=80=94 the larges=
t single-day delivery onto the LME in at least 27 years.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">A few days after the deliveries began, Trafigura laid out its=
 bearish outlook at a conference in London. Analyst Henry Van predicted tha=
t aluminum prices would fall, saying it was seeing =E2=80=9Ca very grim dem=
and picture right now,=E2=80=9D and noting recent smelter restarts.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Trafigura had aluminum and was bearis=
h,=C2=A0so it wanted to sell it. But instead of selling physical aluminum, =
Trafigura popped its aluminum into the LME system =E2=80=94=C2=A0where it w=
as worth <em>less</em>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0and sold it there, missing out o=
n the physical premium but profiting from (1) how many other traders were b=
ullish on aluminum, (2) how many of them wanted physical aluminum=C2=A0and =
(3) how small the door is:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Othe=
r traders are taking the opposite view. Of the metal delivered on to LME wa=
rrant in the past two weeks, about 400,000 tons =E2=80=94 worth about $1 bi=
llion at current prices =E2=80=94 was quickly requested for delivery out ag=
ain. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decision to offload the =
mountain of stock on to the LME has puzzled many of Trafigura=E2=80=99s com=
petitors in the aluminum market, and the scramble to get hold of it has und=
erscored its value to rival traders. Facing soft trading conditions in the =
physical market, Trafigura may have taken the view that the quickest and mo=
st lucrative way to turn a profit on the metal would be to sell it on the L=
ME and collect a share of the rent from future owners.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Traders delivering large volumes to the LME generally enter =E2=
=80=9Crent share=E2=80=9D deals with the warehouse company they=E2=80=99re =
delivering to, meaning they earn a share of the revenues for as long as the=
 metal stays in the warehouse. At a rent of 56 cents a day, the total rent =
on 650,000 tons of aluminum could be worth as much as $133 million a year =
=E2=80=94 more than $200 a ton =E2=80=94 as long as it stays where it is.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If it=E2=80=99s all requested for delivery, =
the total earnings would be a fraction of that amount. Still, it is guarant=
eed to earn a certain amount of money =E2=80=94 about $40 a ton in rent =E2=
=80=94 because the metal is only delivered out at a rate of a few thousand =
tons a day.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The big orders for withdrawal o=
f aluminum have already led to a long queue to take delivery from warehouse=
s in Port Klang operated by Istim Metals. The LME has rules to limit rents =
as soon as warehouse queues exceed a certain threshold, which it introduced=
 after spiralling backlogs for aluminum drew consumer ire and regulatory sc=
rutiny a decade ago.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The obvio=
us question is something like =E2=80=9Cif Trafigura had a lot of aluminum o=
utside of the LME warehouses that it wanted to sell, and a lot of people wa=
nted to buy a lot of aluminum outside of the LME warehouses, why didn=E2=80=
=99t they just trade with each other and skip the line?=E2=80=9D But the an=
swer is apparently that Trafigura analyzed the line and decided it would be=
 more profitable.</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" ce=
llspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
