k;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This was <em>such </em>a good=
 idea that (1) the bond market became reasonably actively traded and effici=
ent, (2) the idea spread far beyond insurance companies (to the point that =
Bill Gross himself managed huge bond portfolios for other institutions and =
individuals) and (3) the edge you could get from it was largely competed aw=
ay.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some insurance companies looke=
d around and said =E2=80=9Cwait, we are insurance companies. We can buy and=
 hold bonds until maturity. If we lend money to companies directly, rather =
than through the big liquid modern bond market, maybe we can charge a highe=
r rate and make more money.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">This was a sensible model for them, since they had locked-up customer mo=
ney and long-term predictable liability schedules, so they could easily hol=
d the loans to maturity.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a sense, =
this is a story of things coming full circle: 1950s insurance companies loa=
ned money to companies and held to maturity without trading the bonds, and =
in 2024 that is also all the rage. But there is an important=C2=A0<em>cultu=
ral=C2=A0</em>difference. In the 1950s, if you did this sort of thing, you =
worked in the bond department of an insurance company, and that was a borin=
g and relatively low-status job that involved literally clipping paper coup=
ons off bonds and mailing them to the company to get your interest payment.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the 2020s, if you do this sort of thing=
, you work for the=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cprivate credit department=E2=80=9D of=C2=
=A0an =E2=80=9Calternative asset manager,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and it=E2=80=99s a =
hot high-status job of pitching to finance=C2=A0leveraged buyouts. The insu=
rance companies are still providing (a chunk=C2=A0of) the money: They are o=
ften limited partners in the private credit funds run by=C2=A0the alternati=
ve asset managers, and in some cases they are owned by the alternative asse=
t managers.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But the people=C2=A0<em>managing=C2=A0</em>the money =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0finding and negotiating=C2=A0and monitoring the private loans =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0are more specialized and get paid more.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Today=C2=A0Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Silas Brown, Paula Seligson, and Est=
eban Duarte <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/355246=
