ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">have a story about</a=
> the bond department of Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co. Wait, no, =
sorry, that=E2=80=99s wrong: They have a story about the private credit (=
=E2=80=9CGlobal Private Finance=E2=80=9D) team at Barings LLC, an investmen=
t management firm that happens to be owned by MassMutual. The Barings priva=
te credit team had a mass defection (and accompanying lawsuits) in March, a=
pparently because =E2=80=A6=C2=A0they didn=E2=80=99t want to work at an ins=
urance company?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a March move=
 that stunned the relatively genteel world of private credit, 22 Barings em=
ployees quit en masse and jumped ship for an obscure startup called Corinth=
ia Global Management Ltd., run by Australian real-estate entrepreneur Paul =
Weightman =E2=80=94 a combative figure known to some as =E2=80=9CWeighty.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to Weightman =
and others with knowledge of the matter, the GPF defectors have been seduce=
d in part by the promise of equity in his firm, something that wasn=E2=80=
=99t on the menu at Barings. While some staffers were making more than $1 m=
illion a year, that=E2=80=99s a fraction of the tens of millions of dollars=
 made by senior peers who=E2=80=99ve cashed in stakes at smaller boutique r=
ivals such as Arcmont Asset Management.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margi=
n: 16px 0;">Tensions at GPF had been building for a while, people familiar =
with the matter say. Many in the team didn=E2=80=99t feel adequately backed=
